  "prompt": "How much does IVF increase a woman's odds of having twins or multiple babies at once?",
  "response": "In vitro fertilization (IVF) does increase the likelihood of multiple pregnancies, but the exact rate can vary based on several factors, including the number of embryos transferred and the woman's age. When more than one embryo is transferred during the IVF process, the probability of having twins or multiples increases significantly.\n\nOn average, the rate of twin pregnancies in women undergoing IVF is about 20-40%, compared to about 1-2% in the general population. The rate of higher-order multiples (triplets or more) can also increase substantially, though this is less common.\n\nMany fertility clinics are now more cautious about the number of embryos they transfer to reduce the risk of multiples due to potential health complications for both the mother and the babies. Single embryo transfer (SET) is increasingly being encouraged depending on individual circumstances, especially for younger women with good-quality embryos.\n\nIt's essential for women considering IVF to discuss the associated risks and benefits, including the likelihood of multiple births, with their fertility specialist.",
